                <head>319. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In telegram 2274 to Moscow, April 23, 1963, the Department of State instructed
                    Under Secretary of State for Political Affairs <persName corresp="#p_HWA1"
                        >Harriman</persName> to proceed to Moscow to discuss the situation in Laos
                    with Soviet Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> and
                    Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName>. “You should recall
                    to the Chairman the mutual commitments exchanged in Vienna and express the
                    Presidentʼs firm belief that unless these commitments and the subsequent Accords
                    reached at Geneva can be effectively implemented, it is difficult for the
                    President to see how any other agreement can be successfully reached and carried
                    out.” For text of telegram 2274 and the memorandum of <persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>ʼs conversation with <persName
                        corresp="#p_KNS1">Khrushchev</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> on April 26, see <ref target="frus1961-63v24#pg_997">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume XXIV, pages
                        997</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v24#pg_998">998</ref> and <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v24#pg_1000">1000</ref>–<ref
                        target="frus1961-63v24#pg_1005">1005</ref>.</p>
            </div>
